<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF208-128-108  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 128 108.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Sept 18 1989 v3 n38 p50(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>AF tunes up for stardust communications system. (Air Force)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Poos, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Stardust is being used for a backup communications system atElmendorf Air Force Base in Alaska, which is part of the defensesystem protecting the Northwestern US.andP;  The conventionalcommunications system uses commercial satellites and 13 long-rangeradar sites throughout the state, but the system could be knockedout by destroying either the satellites or the radars.andO;Electronics technicians looked into meteor-burst communications,which ham radio operators have used for 40 years.andP;  Electricallycharged atoms or ions left in the atmosphere by meteors providesomething for radio waves to bounce off on their way to otherstations.andP;  Meteor Communications Corp constructed a meteorburst-based system for Elmendorf for about $1 million.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Radio CommunicationSatellite CommunicationsNew TechniqueBack-Up SystemsUnited States. Air Force.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   (How stardust communications works). (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>